body:
@vanlim. Just got another problem with CpuSpriteBatch while thinking on solution.

CpuSpriteBatch behaves differently fro SpriteBatch if transformation includes translation (it uses only it's affine part). It does not matter in case of scene2D, but  it produce wrong results if the user set its own transformation like batch.getTransformMatrix().idt().trn(300f, 0f, 0f).

While it is clear why affine is used (speed) the behaviour of CpuSpriteBatch should be equal to one of SpriteBatch. So what should we do?

@vanlim if such usage of transform matrix is not foreseen - OK, I've no problems with that. Just wanted to mention that behaviour is different in comparison to SpriteBatch.

You are right about faed79d. I used a bit oudated data to interpret the exception reason. My fault.

However the exception arise even in the latest nightly. I dig a bit further and found the real problem. One control is a group of two elements - background rectangle and a text. This element zooms from 0 to 1. The rectangle is drawn by ShapeRenderer, so the sprite batch ends before it and begins again after. At this moment CpuSpriteBatch catches singular matrix (from the group scale=0) and raise the Exception.

<b>SSCE:</b>

<pre><code>Group group = new Group();
group.addActor(
    new Actor()
    {
        @Override
        public void draw(Batch batch, float parentAlpha)
        {
            batch.end();
            // some shape renderer code here
            batch.begin();
        }
    }
);
group.addActor(new Image(...));
group.setScale(0f); // Important !
stage.addActor(group);</code></pre>

This code works with SpriteBatch and fails with CpuSpriteBatch.
